      <p>The <span class="concept-highlight" data-node="van-deemter">Van Deemter equation</span> is a fundamental relationship in <span class="concept-highlight" data-node="hplc">HPLC</span> that describes the dependence of <span class="concept-highlight" data-node="plate-height">plate height</span> (H) on the linear velocity of the mobile phase (u). <span class="inline-cite" onclick="showCitation(0)">§ Snyder & Kirkland · P.88 · ¶2</span></p>

      <p>The equation is expressed as <strong>H = A + B/u + Cu</strong>, where each term represents a distinct mass transfer mechanism contributing to <span class="concept-highlight" data-node="band-broadening">band broadening</span>. The A term accounts for <span class="concept-highlight" data-node="eddy-diffusion">eddy diffusion</span> arising from the multiple flow paths through the packed stationary phase. The B term represents longitudinal diffusion of the analyte along the column axis, which is significant at low flow rates. The C term captures the resistance to mass transfer between the mobile and stationary phases, which dominates at high flow rates. <span class="inline-cite" onclick="showCitation(1)">§ Meyer · P.134 · ¶1</span></p>

      <p><span class="concept-highlight" data-node="column-efficiency">Column efficiency</span> is directly related to the Van Deemter equation through the concept of theoretical plates. A lower plate height H corresponds to a greater number of theoretical plates N for a given column length L, since N = L/H. Maximising N while minimising H is therefore the central objective in <span class="concept-highlight" data-node="column-optimization">column optimisation</span>. <span class="inline-cite" onclick="showCitation(2)">§ Neue · P.201 · ¶3</span></p>

      <p>In practice, the Van Deemter curve exhibits a characteristic minimum at an optimal linear velocity u_opt, where the sum of all three terms is minimised. Operating near this optimal velocity yields the highest column efficiency. Modern sub-2µm particle columns shift this minimum to higher velocities, enabling faster separations without sacrificing efficiency — this is the theoretical basis for <span class="concept-highlight" data-node="uhplc">UHPLC</span>. <span class="inline-cite" onclick="showCitation(3)">§ Snyder & Kirkland · P.91 · ¶1</span></p>

